Iron absorption and regulation


See [[2021-Basic Sciences#Abnormal iron metabolism]] <- dysregulated iron absorption

Hepcidin is a key hormone in iron regulation.
It regulated iron release from enterocytes and macrophages.

Increased iron released from macrophages is the major source of iron for the heme synthesis required for erythropoiesis

It also has antimicrobial activity.
Produced by the liver.

Decreased hepcidin production is stimulated by

  • Hypoxia, anaemia, erythropoietic expansion, iron deficiency, ineffetive erythropoiesis (thalassemia)
    Increased production (and decreased iron absorption) are stimulated by
  • increased iron levels
  • inflammation
  • infection, endotoxin

Hepcidin increase is a key factor in anaemia of chronic disease.
+ 1/3 haemosiderin - found within macrophages of the RET, visible under LM when stained with Perl's stain. (probably not assayed in evaluation of iron overload because it's insoluble)
+ Mnemonic : siderin = sediment

Haemochromatosis (HH)

#autosomal-Recessive

Pathogenesis

Caused by mutations (C282Y variant) of the HFE gene.
Increased iron intestinal iron absorption.
Haemochromatosis = iron overload from any cause.
Hereditary haemochromatosis = the inherited disease causing iron overload.

[!INFO] C282Y is necessary but not sufficient for haemochromatosis
Only 20% of C282Y homozygotes actually develop haemochromatosis. In fact, this mutation is quite common in the population.

HH is said to be a low penetrance disease:
HH is now known to be more common than was previously though because of the advent of genetic screening. But many people who carry the mutation are asymptomatic.

Abnormal iron metabolism

  • C282Y causes inappropriately low Hepcidin.
    • High Hepcidin reduces iron deposition in RET. Therefore, in HH, iron deposition occurs first in parenchymal tissue and then in RET. (oppositve of transfusional iron overload)
  • Low hepcidin causes increased intestinal absorption of iron.
  • negative feedback inhibition of iron absorption is disrupted in HH.
  • Significant iron accumulation takes decades.
  • Iron accumulation occurs mostly in LHPP (Liver, heart, pancreas and pituitary).

Clinical features - when to suspect

[!INFO] Classic triad of eatures
The classic triad of cirrhosis, DM, and skin pigmentation ("bronze diabetes") typically occurs after the total-body iron content has reached as much as 20 grams.

  • Most common presentation nowadays is elevated ferritin.

  • Males present around 40; females present after menopause.

  • Symptoms develop because of iron deposition in organs:

    • LFT abnormality - 75%
    • Weakness and lethargy - 75%
    • Skin Hyperpigmentation - 70%
    • DM - 48%
    • Arthrlagia
    • Impotence in males (due to secondary hypogonadism)
    • ECG abnormalities

  • Hepatic iron overload : hepatomegaly, elevated enzymes, fibrosis and cirrhocis, Hepatacellular carcinoma. (HCC)

  • Cardiac iron overload : both Dilated cardiomyopathy and diastolic dysfunction + heart failure, Sinus node dysfunction (Sick sinus syndrome)

  • Endocrine organs

    • Pancreatic iron overload - DM
    • Hypopituitarism, hypogonadism and hypothyroidism - due to reduced production of trophic hormones.

Marfan syndrome

[!TIP] Marfan mnemonic

S also for subluxation of lens.

#autosomalDominant
Defect is in FBN1 gene encoding the fibrillin-1 protein which is a connective tissue protein.

Q 13: Wilsons disease

#2021BSQ-NOV Q54

Description: Copper is absorbed from the stomach and small intestine;

Caused by #autosomal-Recessive defect in ATP7B gene on Chromosome 13 which affects a copper transporting ATPase.

Organs affected:

[!TIP] Eyes and basal ganglia and of course liver

  • Liver: histology is unreliable, need to quantitatively measure copper content; Acute / chronic hepatitis -> The presentation in children.
  • basal ganglia [[striatumBasalGanglia.png]] -> Cavitation -> tremmor, dysarthria, dementia; The presentation in young adults.
  • Renal tubules -> tubular degeneration
  • Bones -> erosions
  • Eyes -> Kayser Fleischer ring. (requires slit lamp)
  • Treatment: lifetime penicillamine, trientine and zinc acetate for asymptomatic cases.
